biogHists.text:
Farmer, banker, missionary and stake president for the Mormon Church.

From the guide to the George Tilton Hyde oral history transcript, 1956, (L. Tom Perry Special Collections)

Mormon accountant, banker, lawyer, and employee for the Federal Radio Commission which later became the Federal Communications Commission. He held a number of important positions in that agency including chairman.

From the description of Hyde photographs, circa 1940s-1970s. (Unknown). WorldCat record id: 367947624 From the description of Rosel H. Hyde papers, 1926-1984. (Unknown). WorldCat record id: 365145289 From the guide to the Rosel H. Hyde papers, 1926-1984, (L. Tom Perry Special Collections)

                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Oral history transcript, 1956.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>Photocopy of a transcript of an interview done with George Hyde by his son, Rosel H. Hyde, on 16 Aug. 1956.  George was raised in Kaysville, Utah, served on a Mormon mission to the Southern States, and spent most of his adult life in Idaho.  He lived in Downey and was stake president of the Pocatello Stake for the Mormon Church for twenty-five years. </abstract>
                  <name>

                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
